a, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saint-Amand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Haitian: variant of <b>Saint-Amand</b> (see   St. Amand  ) and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. This form of the surname is very rare in France; it is more common in Haiti."],"variants":[{"name":"St. Amand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Girard, Aurore, Emile, Lucien, Normand, Alyre, Andre, Armand, Camille, Clovis, Francois.","French (<b>Saint-Amand</b>): habitational name from any of several places called Saint-Amand (from the dedication of their churches to Saint Amandus), or a nickname with the prefix <i>Saint</i> as an (ironic) attachment to the personal name or surname   Amand  . Compare   Saintamand   and   St. Amant  .","Haitian (also <b>Saint-Amand</b>): from <i>Saint-Amand</i>, a nickname, ornamental name, or personal name composed of the French prefix <i>Saint</i> and the personal name   Amand  . This surname is rare in Haiti. Compare   Saintamand  ."]}]},{"name":"Huston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (Derry and Antrim): variant of   Houston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Houston","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Houston (Renfrewshire), from the genitive case of the personal name   Hugh   + Middle English, Older Scots <i>ton</i> ‘town, village, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’). The landlord in question was a certain Hugo de Paduinan, who held the place <i>c.</i> 1160. The Scottish surname is also common in Ulster.","Irish: variant of   McCutcheon   from <b>Mac Uisdein</b> or <b>Mac Uistein</b>.","History: In 1836 the newly founded city of Houston, TX, was named in honor of Sam Houston (1793–1863), soldier and statesman. As commander in chief of the Texan army he achieved Texas independence from Mexico by routing the army of the Mexican general Santa Anna. His ancestors were Ulster Scots who had emigrated to Philadelphia, PA, in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Huston de Saint-Amand was born in 1080, in Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1150, in Saint-Omer-en-Chaussée, Oise, Picardie, France, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1080–1150":"1080–1150","1110–1179":"1110–1179","1080":"1080","1179":"1179","1110":"1110","1150":"1150","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Saint-Omer-en-Chaussée, Oise, Picardie, France":"Saint-Omer-en-Chaussée, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1080–1150":"1080–1150","1110–1179":"1110–1179","1080":"1080","1179":"1179","1110":"1110","1150":"1150","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Ranska","Saint-Omer-en-Chaussée, Oise, Picardie, France":"Saint-Omer-en-Chaussée, Oise, Picardie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1080–1150":"1080–1150","1110–1179":"1110–1179","1080":"1080","1179":"1179","1110":"1110","1150":"1150","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Saint-Omer-en-Chaussée, Oise, Picardie, France":"Saint-Omer-en-Chaussée, Oise, Picardie, France","lifeSummary":"Huston de Saint-Amand est né en 1080, à Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1150, à Saint-Omer-en-Chaussée, Oise, Picardie, France, à l’âge de 70 ans."},"de":{"1080–1150":"1080–1150","1110–1179":"1110–1179","1080":"1080","1179":"1179","1110":"1110","1150":"1150","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Fra